You can create class that extends [android.app.Application][1]. In that class, you can throw runtime exception to crash the app, [if app is running on emulator][2]. 

Note that, there&#39;s no bulletproof solution as anyone can decompile your app with free tools and remove those checks easily.

```java
import android.app.Application;
import android.os.Build;

public class App extends Application {

    @Override
    public void onCreate() {
        super.onCreate();

        if (isEmulator()) throw new IllegalStateException();
    }

    private boolean isEmulator() {
        return (Build.BRAND.startsWith(&quot;generic&quot;) &amp;&amp; Build.DEVICE.startsWith(&quot;generic&quot;))
                || Build.FINGERPRINT.startsWith(&quot;generic&quot;)
                || Build.FINGERPRINT.startsWith(&quot;unknown&quot;)
